00:37:37,480 --> 00:37:41,480
Well, a dialect geographer using a list of only 30 words

476
00:37:41,480 --> 00:37:45,480
can usually place a person within 20 miles of his home locality

477
00:37:45,480 --> 00:37:49,480
so long as he lives in the eastern part of the United States.

478
00:37:49,480 --> 00:37:54,480
Dialect geographers began charting their monumental linguistic atlas

479
00:37:54,480 --> 00:37:56,480
in the east in 1929

480
00:37:56,480 --> 00:37:59,480
and have been painstakingly working their way to the west.

481
00:37:59,480 --> 00:38:02,480
Dr. Hans Kurath of the University of Michigan

482
00:38:02,480 --> 00:38:04,480
has conducted a good part of this research.

483
00:38:04,480 --> 00:38:07,480
He and his dialect experts are traveling around the country

484
00:38:07,480 --> 00:38:09,480
for the past 25 years,

485
00:38:09,480 --> 00:38:12,480
asking people what words they use for all sorts of things.

486
00:38:12,480 --> 00:38:15,480
They've recorded dialect differences in words

487
00:38:15,480 --> 00:38:17,480
and how they're pronounced.

488
00:38:17,480 --> 00:38:21,480
Perhaps Dr. Kurath will show us how the atlas is put together.

489
00:38:21,480 --> 00:38:27,480
Well, you see, the atlas contains hundreds of maps showing speech differences

490
00:38:27,480 --> 00:38:31,480
and their geographical boundaries, which we call isoglosses.

491
00:38:31,480 --> 00:38:35,480
May I show you a few examples?

492
00:38:36,480 --> 00:38:44,480
This isogloss sets off the area in which riddle cakes are called fritter.

493
00:38:44,480 --> 00:38:50,480
This here around Philadelphia shows the area where they call them hotcakes.

494
00:38:50,480 --> 00:38:57,480
Over here they're called flannertakes to the south of it, batter cakes.

495
00:38:57,480 --> 00:39:05,480
It is on the basis of isoglosses like these that we establish the dialect ban.

496
00:39:05,480 --> 00:39:08,480
Thank you, Dr. Kurath.

497
00:39:08,480 --> 00:39:11,480
Man takes his speech ways with him wherever he goes.

498
00:39:11,480 --> 00:39:15,480
As the dialects flowed westward the way our population did,

499
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:18,480
the strands unraveled and began to overlap.

500
00:39:18,480 --> 00:39:20,480
Here's how they traveled.

501
00:39:20,480 --> 00:39:23,480
Western New England accents,

502
00:39:23,480 --> 00:39:26,480
coast speech,

503
00:39:26,480 --> 00:39:28,480
southern mountain accents,

504
00:39:28,480 --> 00:39:30,480
plantation speech,

505
00:39:30,480 --> 00:39:32,480
Texas accents,

506
00:39:32,480 --> 00:39:37,480
but down east talk in the state of Maine has stayed put.

507
00:39:37,480 --> 00:39:40,480
This research has revealed the paths people have taken

508
00:39:40,480 --> 00:39:43,480
when they migrated from one part of the country to another,

509
00:39:43,480 --> 00:39:47,480
shown the changes going on in American speech patterns.

510
00:39:47,480 --> 00:39:51,480
This research has unearthed hitherto unrecorded dialects.

511
00:39:51,480 --> 00:39:54,480
There's also marked off areas where big cities have influenced

512
00:39:54,480 --> 00:39:57,480
the speech ways of neighboring localities.

513
00:39:57,480 --> 00:40:00,480
This atlas is a most impressive achievement

514
00:40:00,480 --> 00:40:04,480
at one branch of the science of linguistics, Dr. L.

515
00:40:04,480 --> 00:40:06,480
It may be linguistics, it may be impressive,

516
00:40:06,480 --> 00:40:08,480
it may even be an achievement in one branch,

517
00:40:08,480 --> 00:40:11,480
but don't try to convince me that it's a science.

518
00:40:11,480 --> 00:40:14,480
A science is test tubes, telescopes,

519
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:17,480
microscopes, and chromium-plated machines.

520
00:40:17,480 --> 00:40:20,480
Actually, linguistics has its own share of hardware.

521
00:40:20,480 --> 00:40:21,480
Hardware?

522
00:40:21,480 --> 00:40:24,480
Yes, that's what scientists call their machines.

523
00:40:24,480 --> 00:40:26,480
Before you can build a piece of hardware,

524
00:40:26,480 --> 00:40:29,480
you have to know exactly what you want it to do.

525
00:40:29,480 --> 00:40:34,480
That calls for research, imagination, would you please?

