00:43:15,480 --> 00:43:19,480
Yes, Audrey, the automatic digit recognizer

576
00:43:19,480 --> 00:43:22,480
can identify numbers spoken into a telephone.

577
00:43:22,480 --> 00:43:25,480
And how about the voice typewriter?

578
00:43:25,480 --> 00:43:29,480
He takes dictation and types words as they are spoken.

579
00:43:29,480 --> 00:43:31,480
See.

580
00:43:33,480 --> 00:43:38,480
You read it.

581
00:43:38,480 --> 00:43:41,480
It's like a secretary who never makes a mistake.

582
00:43:41,480 --> 00:43:44,480
No, they're easily confused by different voices

583
00:43:44,480 --> 00:43:46,480
and different accents.

584
00:43:46,480 --> 00:43:48,480
Voice typewriters are still pretty crude.

585
00:43:48,480 --> 00:43:52,480
What about machines that talk to each other?

586
00:43:52,480 --> 00:43:55,480
Yes, electronic computing machines

587
00:43:55,480 --> 00:43:57,480
can transmit data to each other

588
00:43:57,480 --> 00:43:59,480
over ordinary telephone circuits.

589
00:43:59,480 --> 00:44:01,480
Those machines will soon learn that it's a lot easier

590
00:44:01,480 --> 00:44:03,480
to get into this talking business

591
00:44:03,480 --> 00:44:04,480
than it is to get out of it.

592
00:44:04,480 --> 00:44:06,480
Out of it.

593
00:44:06,480 --> 00:44:09,480
I never dreamed machines could be so smart.

594
00:44:09,480 --> 00:44:11,480
I'd have a tea party conversation with a machine.

